# Docker-first development

All development commands MUST run inside Docker containers unless impossible (e.g. `docker compose` itself, Git, editing files).

## Command patterns

Containers already running (`docker compose up`):

```bash
docker compose exec app <command>
```

One-off command (containers not running):

```bash
docker compose run --rm app <command>
```

## Examples

```bash
# Install dependencies
docker compose run --rm app npm install

# Create Next.js project
docker compose run --rm app npx create-next-app@latest . --typescript --tailwind --app --no-git

# Dev server (via compose up)
docker compose up

# Migrations
docker compose exec app npm run db:migrate

# Tests / lint
docker compose exec app npm test
docker compose exec app npm run lint
```

## CSS / HMR in development

- `next.config.ts` disables Turbopack dev filesystem cache and sends `Cache-Control: no-store` in development.
- Compose sets `CHOKIDAR_*` / `WATCHPACK_POLLING*` so file changes propagate from WSL bind mounts.
- If styles still look stale: `docker compose exec app npm run dev:clean` (clears `.next` once), then normal `docker compose up` afterward.
- Browser: prefer a hard reload once after config changes; DevTools → Network → "Disable cache" (while open) also helps.

## Rules for the agent

- Do NOT run `npm`, `npx`, `node`, migration, or test commands on the host.
- Execute them via `docker compose exec app` or `docker compose run --rm app`.
- No prior user approval is required for commands inside containers.
- Host-side exceptions: `docker compose`, `git`, file edits, `openspec` CLI.

## Services

| Service | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `app` | Next.js, npm, npx, Drizzle |
| `db` | PostgreSQL 16 (local dev) |
